<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-average-rate-of-change" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Average Rate of Change</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.6 Graphical Methods
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Determine the average rate of change from a graph over a given interval.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        15 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To discover that the average rate of change is constant for linear functions but varies for non-linear functions over different intervals.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        Encourage learners to compare the "steepness" of the line connecting two points on a curve at different parts of the graph.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

    <!-- Add Activity -->

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                Imagine a car accelerating. Its distance <m>s</m> (meters) after <m>t</m> seconds is <m>s = t^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What you need</alert>
            </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                           <p> 
                             Graph paper
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Ruler
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Calculator
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Plot the graph of <m>s = t^2</m> for <m>0 \le t \le 5</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the average speed (rate of change) between <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the average speed between <m>t = 3</m> and <m>t = 5</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw straight lines (secants) connecting the points used in steps 2 and 3.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compare the gradients of these two lines. What does this tell you about how the car is moving?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the calculation of the average rate of change using the gradient formula.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>The Secant Line:</alert> A line connecting two distinct points on a curve is called a secant line.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Average Rate of Change:</alert> The gradient of the secant line represents the average rate of change of the function over that interval.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The <alert>average rate of change</alert> of a function <m>y = f(x)</m> between <m>x = x_1</m> and <m>x = x_2</m> is given by:
                        <me>\text{Average Rate of Change} = \frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1}</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Graphically, this is the gradient of the <alert>secant line</alert> passing through <m>(x_1, y_1)</m> and <m>(x_2, y_2)</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <term>Secant line:</term> is a straight line that cuts a curve at two different points.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <image xml:id="img-secant-illustration-avg" width="65%">
            <latex-image label="Secant Line Illustration">
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                    \draw[-&gt;] (-0.5,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {$x$};
                    \draw[-&gt;] (0,-0.5) -- (0,5) node[above] {$y$};
                    \draw[thick, blue, domain=0.5:4] plot (\x, {0.2*\x*\x + 1});
                    % Secant
                    \coordinate (A) at (1, 1.2);
                    \coordinate (B) at (3.5, 3.45);
                    \draw[red, dashed] (0.5, 0.75) -- (4, 3.9) node[right] {Secant line};
                    \filldraw (A) circle (1.5pt) node[below right] {$(x_1, y_1)$};
                    \filldraw (B) circle (1.5pt) node[above left] {$(x_2, y_2)$};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the average rate of change for the function <m>y = x^2 + 2x</m> between the points where <m>x = 1</m> and <m>x = 3</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First, find the <m>y</m>-coordinates:
            </p>
            <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                <row>
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>15</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                Now, calculate the gradient:
                <me>\text{Gradient} = \frac{15 - 3}{3 - 1} = \frac{12}{2} = 6</me>
            </p>
            <image width="65%">
                <latex-image label="QuadraticSecant Line">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm, y=0.25cm]

                       % Grid
                        \draw[help lines, color=gray!40,
                            xstep=1, ystep=2]
                            (-0.5,-1) grid (4.5,16);


                        % Axes
                        \draw[->] (-0.5,0) -- (4.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
                        \draw[->] (0,-1) -- (0,16.5) node[above] {$y$};

                        % Quadratic curve
                        \draw[thick, blue, domain=0:3.4, smooth]
                            plot (\x, {\x*\x + 2*\x});

                        % Secant line
                        \draw[red, dashed] (1,3) -- (3,15);

                        % Points
                        \filldraw (1,3) circle (2pt)
                            node[left] {$(1,3)$};

                        \filldraw (3,15) circle (2pt)
                            node[right] {$(3,15)$};

                        % Delta x
                        \draw[thick, black, dashed]
                            (1,3) -- (3,3);

                        \node at (2,1.5) {$\Delta x = 2$};

                        % Delta y
                        \draw[thick, black, dashed]
                            (3,3) -- (3,15);

                        \node at (3.8,9) {$\Delta y = 12$};

                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p>
                The average rate of change is <m>6</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the average rate of change for the function <m>y = x^3 - 4x</m> from <m>x = -1</m> to <m>x = 2</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Evaluate the function at the endpoints:
            </p>
            <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                <row>
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                Calculate the average rate of change:
                <me>\text{Rate} = \frac{0 - 3}{2 - (-1)} = \frac{-3}{3} = -1</me>
            </p>
            <image xml:id="img-example-cubic-avg" width="65%">
                <latex-image label="Cubic_Function_Secant Line">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                        \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-2,-4) grid (3,4);
                        \draw[-&gt;] (-2,0) -- (3,0) node[right] {$x$};
                        \draw[-&gt;] (0,-4) -- (0,4) node[above] {$y$};
                        \draw[thick, blue, domain=-2.1:2.3, samples=60] plot (\x, {\x*\x*\x - 4*\x});
                        \draw[red, dashed] (-1.5, 4.5) -- (2.5, -1.5);
                        \filldraw (-1,3) circle (2pt) node[above left] {$(-1, 3)$};
                        \filldraw (2,0) circle (2pt) node[below left] {$(2, 0)$};
                        % Gradient triangle
                        \draw[thick, black, dashed] (-1,3) -- (2,3) node[midway, above] {$\Delta x = 3$};
                        \draw[thick, black, dashed] (2,3) -- (2,0) node[midway, right] {$\Delta y = -3$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The population <m>P</m> of a town (in thousands) is modeled by <m>P = 5 + 0.1t^2</m>, where <m>t</m> is years since 2020. Find the average annual population growth rate between 2022 and 2025.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <m>2022</m> corresponds to <m>t = 2</m> and 2025 corresponds to <m>t = 5</m>.
            </p>
            <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                <row>
                    <cell><m>t</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5.4</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5.9</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>6.6</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>7.5</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                Average growth rate = <m>\frac{7.5 - 5.4}{5 - 2} = \frac{2.1}{3} = 0.7</m> thousand people per year.
            </p>
            <image xml:id="img-example-pop-avg" width="65%">
                <latex-image label="Population Growth with Secant Line">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                        \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (0,4) grid (6,9);
                        \draw[-&gt;] (0,4) -- (6,4) node[right] {$t$};
                        \draw[-&gt;] (0,4) -- (0,9) node[above] {$P$};
                        \draw[thick, blue, domain=0:6] plot (\x, {5 + 0.1*\x*\x});
                        \draw[red, dashed] (1, 4.7) -- (6, 8.2);
                        \filldraw (2,5.4) circle (3pt);
                        \filldraw (5,7.5) circle (3pt);
                        \draw[thick, black, dashed] (2,5.4) -- (5,5.4) node[midway, below] {$\Delta t = 3$};
                        \draw[thick, black, dashed] (5,5.4) -- (5,7.5) node[midway, right] {$\Delta P = 2.1$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Calculate the average rate of change of <m>y = 3x^2 - 5</m> between <m>x = 0</m> and <m>x = 2</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    When <m>x = 0, y = 3(0)^2 - 5 = -5</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    When <m>x = 2, y = 3(2)^2 - 5 = 12 - 5 = 7</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Average rate of change = <m>\frac{7 - (-5)}{2 - 0} = \frac{12}{2} = 6</m>.
                </p>
                <image xml:id="img-ex-secant-quad-avg" width="65%">
                    <latex-image label="Quadratic_Secant Line">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                            \draw[help lines, color=gray!30, step=1] (-1,-6) grid (4,10);
                            \draw[-&gt;] (-1,0) -- (4,0) node[right] {$x$};
                            \draw[-&gt;] (0,-6) -- (0,10) node[above] {$y$};
                            \draw[thick, blue, domain=-0.5:2.2] plot (\x, {3*\x*\x - 5});
                            \draw[red, dashed] (-0.5, -8) -- (2.5, 10);
                            \filldraw (0,-5) circle (2pt);
                            \filldraw (2,7) circle (2pt);
                            % Gradient triangle from (0,-5) to (2,7)
                            \draw[thick, black, dashed] (0,-5) -- (2,-5) node[midway, below] {$\Delta x = 2$};
                            \draw[thick, black, dashed] (2,-5) -- (2,7) node[midway, right] {$\Delta y = 12$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For the function <m>y = \frac{1}{x}</m>, find the average rate of change from <m>x = 1</m> to <m>x = 4</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                When <m>x = 1, y = 1</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                When <m>x = 4, y = 0.25</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Average rate = <m>\frac{0.25 - 1}{4 - 1} = \frac{-0.75}{3} = -0.25</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A tank is filled with water. The volume <m>V</m> at time <m>t</m> is <m>V = 2t^2 + 10</m>. Find the average rate at which volume increases between <m>t = 1</m> and <m>t = 4</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                At <m>t = 1, V = 2(1)^2 + 10 = 12</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                At <m>t = 4, V = 2(4)^2 + 10 = 32 + 10 = 42</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    Average rate = <m>\frac{42 - 12}{4 - 1} = \frac{30}{3} = 10</m> units/s.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the average rate of change of <m>f(x) = x^2 - 2x</m> on the interval <m>[1, 4]</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p><m>3</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{AROC} \amp= \frac{f(4) - f(1)}{4 - 1} = \frac{(16-8)-(1-2)}{3} = \frac{8-(-1)}{3} = \frac{9}{3} = 3</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A stone is dropped from a cliff and falls freely. Its distance below the cliff top (in metres) after <m>t</m> seconds is <m>s(t) = 5t^2</m>.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Find the average speed over <m>2 \le t \le 4</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Find the average speed over <m>3 \le t \le 5</m>.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>30 m/s</p></li>
                    <li><p>40 m/s</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\frac{s(4)-s(2)}{4-2} = \frac{80-20}{2} = 30 \text{ m/s}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\frac{s(5)-s(3)}{5-3} = \frac{125-45}{2} = 40 \text{ m/s}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The temperature in Nairobi on a certain day (in °C) is modelled by
                    <m>T(h) = -h^2 + 6h + 14</m>, where <m>h</m> is hours after 6 am.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Find the average rate of change of temperature from <m>h = 1</m> to <m>h = 4</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Give the units and interpret the answer in context.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p><m>1</m> °C per hour</p></li>
                    <li><p>The temperature rose, on average, by 1°C per hour between 7 am and 10 am.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>T(4) \amp= -16+24+14 = 22, \quad T(1) = -1+6+14 = 19</mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{AROC} \amp= \frac{T(4)-T(1)}{4-1} = \frac{22-19}{3} = 1 \text{ °C/h}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>The units are degrees Celsius per hour. The temperature was rising at an average rate of 1°C per hour between 7 am and 10 am.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For <m>f(x) = x^2</m>, calculate the average rate of change over <m>[2,\ 2+h]</m> for each value of <m>h</m> in the table. Describe the pattern you observe as <m>h</m> gets smaller.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <tabular top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor" halign="center">
                        <row header="yes">
                            <cell><m>h</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>f(2+h)</m></cell>
                            <cell>AROC <m>= \dfrac{f(2+h)-f(2)}{h}</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row><cell><m>1</m></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                        <row><cell><m>0.5</m></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                        <row><cell><m>0.1</m></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                        <row><cell><m>0.01</m></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                    </tabular>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <tabular top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor" halign="center">
                        <row header="yes">
                            <cell><m>h</m></cell><cell><m>f(2+h)</m></cell><cell>AROC</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row><cell>1</cell><cell>9</cell><cell>5</cell></row>
                        <row><cell>0.5</cell><cell>6.25</cell><cell>4.5</cell></row>
                        <row><cell>0.1</cell><cell>4.41</cell><cell>4.1</cell></row>
                        <row><cell>0.01</cell><cell>4.0401</cell><cell>4.01</cell></row>
                    </tabular>
                </p>
                <p>The AROC approaches <m>4</m> as <m>h \to 0</m>.</p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Expanding: <m>f(2+h) = (2+h)^2 = 4 + 4h + h^2</m>, so
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{AROC} = \frac{f(2+h)-f(2)}{h} = \frac{4h+h^2}{h} = 4+h.</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <tabular top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor" halign="center">
                        <row header="yes">
                            <cell><m>h</m></cell><cell><m>f(2+h)</m></cell><cell>AROC <m>= 4+h</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row><cell>1</cell><cell>9</cell><cell>5</cell></row>
                        <row><cell>0.5</cell><cell>6.25</cell><cell>4.5</cell></row>
                        <row><cell>0.1</cell><cell>4.41</cell><cell>4.1</cell></row>
                        <row><cell>0.01</cell><cell>4.0401</cell><cell>4.01</cell></row>
                    </tabular>
                </p>
                <p>
                    As <m>h \to 0</m>, AROC <m>\to 4</m>. This limiting value is the <em>instantaneous</em> rate of change of <m>f(x)=x^2</m> at <m>x=2</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A matatu departs Nairobi. Its distance from the city centre (km) after <m>t</m> hours is <m>d(t) = 4t^2 - t</m>.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Find the average speed between <m>t = 1</m> h and <m>t = 3</m> h.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Find the average speed between <m>t = 2</m> h and <m>t = 2.5</m> h.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>15 km/h</p></li>
                    <li><p>17 km/h</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p> Calculating distance, 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>d(3) \amp = 36-3 = 33 </mrow>
                                <mrow>d(1) \amp = 4-1 = 3</mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{Average speed} \amp= \frac{33-3}{3-1} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{30}{2} = 15 \text{ km/h}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>d(2.5) \amp= 4(6.25)-2.5 = 22.5</mrow>
                                <mrow>d(2) \amp = 16-2 = 14</mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{Average speed} \amp= \frac{22.5-14}{2.5-2} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{8.5}{0.5} = 17 \text{ km/h}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The function <m>f(x) = -x^2 + 4x</m> models the height (in metres) of a thrown ball above the ground at time <m>x</m> seconds.
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p>Find the average rate of change on <m>[1, 3]</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Find the average rate of change on <m>[3, 5]</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>What does the sign of each answer tell you about the ball's motion?</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><p><m>0</m> (same height at <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=3</m>)</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>-4</m> m/s</p></li>
                    <li><p>Zero means the ball returned to the same height; negative means it is falling on average.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>f(1)=3</m> and <m>f(3)=-9+12=3</m>, so AROC <m>= \dfrac{3-3}{2} = 0</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>f(5) = -25+20 = -5, \quad f(3) = 3</mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{AROC} = \frac{-5-3}{5-3} = \frac{-8}{2} = -4 \text{ m/s}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>A positive AROC means the ball is rising on average; zero means it returns to the same height; negative means it is falling on average over the interval.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For <m>f(x) = x^2 + 3x</m>, find the value of <m>x</m> at which the average rate of change over the interval <m>[x,\ x+1]</m> equals <m>7</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p><m>x = 1.5</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{AROC} \amp= \frac{f(x+1)-f(x)}{1}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp= (x+1)^2+3(x+1) - x^2-3x</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp= x^2+2x+1+3x+3 - x^2-3x = 2x+4</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Setting <m>2x+4 = 7</m> gives <m>x = 1.5</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

